<HEADLINE> Iraq Protests Violations of Airspace by U.S., </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Saturday protested to the
Arab League against the continued violations of its airspace by
warplanes of the United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
In a protest message sent to Arab League Secretary General
Esmat Abdel-Meguid, Iraqi permanent delegate to the league Sultan
Shavi said the warplanes of the two countries carried out 288
sorties in the first week of July.
</P>
<P>
Shavi demanded Abdel-Meguid to intervene to halt the aggressive
actions that threaten Iraq's sovereignty and territorial
integration.
</P>
<P>
The actions by the two western allies panic civilians and
damage property, he said.
</P>
<P>
The airstrikes also constitute a flagrant violation of the Arab
League Charter, the joint Arab defense pact, the United Nations
Charter and the international laws, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi diplomat underlined his country's right to demand
compensation for material and moral damage.
</P>
<P>
Since December, warplanes of the U.S. and Britain have been
patroling the two no-fly zones in the north and south of Iraq,
which were set up after the 1991 Gulf War. The warplanes have
attacked Iraq's military and civilian targets, leaving scores of
people dead and properties damaged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
