<HEADLINE> Zanzibar President Says Treason Case to Be Decided </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar President Salmin
Amour said Saturday the judiciary is the sole competent authority
to determine the fate of the treason case facing 18 opposition
Civic United Front (CUF) members who have been detained since
late 1997.  Opening a two-day youth meeting in Zanzibar, Amour
said he has no mandate to dictate terms on the matter that is
being handled by the court.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting of the National Executive Committee of the youth
 organization Vijana of the ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM), he
urged people to wait before the court decides whether to convict
the suspects or set them free for whatever suitable reasons it
deems fit.  Amour pointed out that under the current system and
separation of powers, it is not wise to interfere with the work
of the judiciary by ordering the release of the accused persons,
reports from Zanzibar said.
</P>
<P>
"Let us give the judiciary a chance to accomplish its
proceedings and decide the way it sees fit," Amour told the
gathering which among other things will discuss the political
situation and the crusade against corruption in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibar President said that the rule of law must be given a
chance to ensure that all the people become law abiding citizens.
He said this is a prerequisite and guarantee for national
stability and solidarity.
</P>
<P>
The accused persons in the treason case include four members of
the Zanzibar House of Representatives. They are charged with
plotting to overthrow the isles government and remove President
Amour from power.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar's CCM, under Amour who was seeking a second term as
president of the isles, claimed a narrow victory over the CUF in
the 1995 elections, but CUF questioned the result and locked
horns with CCM in a series of conflicts during the past four
years.
</P>
<P>
Brokered by the Commonwealth, the two political parties last
month signed a landmark national reconciliation agreement to
settle the political impasse in Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar's twin islands joined Tanganyika in 1964 to form the
United Republic of Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
