<HEADLINE> Ulster Unionist Leader Trimble Hints to Stay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Ulster Unionist leader David
Trimble Saturday given the strongest of indications that he will
not stand down as Northern Ireland First Minister.
</P>
<P>
In an interview for a BBC Radio program, Trimble said that
despite the resignation of Deputy First Minister Seamus Mallon,
for him to do the same could send a signal that the political
process was disintegrating.
</P>
<P>
Mallon, deputy leader of the Social Democratic and Labour Party
(SDLP), resigned Thursday after the failed attempt to set up a
power-sharing assembly under the Good Friday Agreement.
</P>
<P>
It had been expected that Trimble might step down as first
minister after Seamus Mallon's resignation, but the Ulster
Unionist leader said that the British and Irish Governments were
privately briefing journalists that he should stay.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said the events of the past week had proved his party
was not bluffing about decommissioning and that he was not
interested in a fudge.
</P>
<P>
"If I were to resign would that not make it appear that the
position is crumbling further, that the process is disintegrating
further," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although it is likely that former U.S. Senator George Mitchell,
who brokered last year's Good Friday Agreement, will be asked to
chair the next attempt to solve the decommissioning dispute,
Trimble said the parties would have to solve it themselves.
</P>
<P>
Northern Irish police Saturday charged four men after finding
an arms cache, underlining the daunting task facing George
Mitchell as he tries again to bring peace to the British province.
</P>
</TEXT>
