<HEADLINE> Egyptian Journalist, Professor Fined for Libeling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian court on Saturday fined
a journalist and a professor 10,000 Egyptians pounds (2,945 U.S.
dollars) each for libeling a prominent Sunni cleric in a newspaper
article that accused him of corruption.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo Criminal Court also ordered the two men to pay 501
pounds (147 dollars) each as temporary compensation to Mohammed
Sayyed Tantawi, the grand sheik of Al-Azhar University in Cairo,
the world's best-known university for Sunni Islamic studies,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The journalist, Mustafa Noureddin, was taken to court by the
government prosecutor for writing an article in the opposition
Al-Ahrar daily, in which he alleged that Tantawi was corrupt, the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Yehia Ismail Halboush, a professor at Al-Azhar who opposed
Tantawi, was convicted of providing the information for the
article last year, it added.
</P>
<P>
Ismail was one of the members of the Al-Azhar Ulama Front,
which brought together militant clergymen into Al-Azhar to oppose
the more moderate Tantawi. The government banned the front in June
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
