<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi, Myanmar Officials Hold "Cordial" Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi and Myanmar foreign
ministers held "cordial" talks here on Saturday on the entire
gamut of bilateral relations, Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are considering formation of a (joint) commission to
resolve some issues between us" and to promote all-round
cooperation between the two neighbors, Azad told reporters after
official talks with his Myanmar counterpart, U Win Aung, at the
Meghna State Guest House this evening.
</P>
<P>
Terming the two-hour talks as "fruitful," Azad said the talks,
covering such issues as repatriation of Rohingya refugees staying
in Bangladesh, land mining and border trade, were held in a
"cordial" atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar foreign minister, who arrived here earlier Saturday
on a three-day official visit to Bangladesh after concluding his
visit to Sri Lanka, said the two sides expressed their will to
resolve the issues existing between them.
</P>
<P>
The proposed commission would be formed considering different
tires to take up various issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers needed to have more meetings and there should
be more exchange of visits between the two countries at different
levels to resolve various issues, Aung said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that senior official-level meeting, which
remained stalled for more than two years, would be resumed. The
last and 21st round of senior official-level meeting between the
two sides was held in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question, Aung said the refugee issue would be
solved, but he gave no time-frame. Over 20,000 Myanmar refugees,
known here as Rohingya refugees, are living in two camps in Cox's
Bazar, southeast Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
About 250,000 Rohingyas crossed Bangladesh border in 1991, and
about 230,000 of them have been repatriated under a memorandum of
understanding between Bangladesh and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation of the refugees to Myanmar stopped in July
1997 reportedly as a result of the refugees' refusal to return.
</P>
<P>
The official BSS news agency said that since the repatriation
was resumed in November last year and up to June this year, only
378 Rohingyas had been repatriated, and during this period, 621
babies were born in the camps and 78 died, leaving an additional
543 to be included in the total number of refugees awaiting
repatriation.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the two foreign ministers would meet again on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Aung is scheduled to call on President Shahabuddin Ahmed and
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
