<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Rebels Hand Over 192 Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Revolutionary United Front
(RUF) of Sierra Leone has handed over 192 abducted children to the
United Nations special representative in the country, said reports
reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The group of children and a few adults were brought to capital
Freetown in two trucks from Magbeni, about 60 kilometers east of
the capital and was formally received by U.N. Special
Representative Francis Okello and West African peace-keeping force
of ECOMOG Commander Major Gen. Felix Mujakpero.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release issued by the U.N. Children's Fund
(UNICEF), many of the children are poorly clad, visibly tired,
undernourished and complained of hunger and thirst.
</P>
<P>
The release added that most of the 68 females were between the
ages of 14 and 20, and at least a quarter of them were pregnant
with seven lactating adolescent mothers.
</P>
<P>
The rebels who signed a peace agreement on July 7 with the
Sierra Leonean government have been accused of killing, mutilating
and raping civilians.
</P>
<P>
The rebel RUF has freed about 1,000 of the estimated 3,000
children they are believed to be holding.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, hundreds of former rebels have been streaming into
capital Freetown since last Wednesday from the bush following the
peace agreement signed in Togolese capital of Lome.
</P>
<P>
The influx of the unarmed rebels has prompted fear among
Freetown residents who expressed concern that the rebels were
entering the city before the start of planned disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace agreement, the rebels are supposed to go to
U.N.- monitored disarmament centers to be set up by the end of
August.
</P>
<P>
The government of President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah who signed the
agreement with rebel leader Foday Sankoh was also concerned about
the rebel influx. 
</P>
</TEXT>
