<DOCNO> XIE19990718.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Threatens to Kill Intruders Within LOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- India declared Saturday that
intruders found on its side of the so-called Line of Control (LOC)
would be "shot and killed" as the extended deadline for withdrawal
of infiltrators ended this morning.
</P>
<P>
"The deadline for withdrawal has expired this morning and,
therefore, any Pakistan Army soldier or activity observed on our
side of the LOC will be treated as hostile and targeted
accordingly," an Indian army spokesman told the press here.
</P>
<P>
"While our troops are fully geared to neutralize any enemy
remnants, no enemy activity has been reported by our ground troops
in any of the sectors since this morning," he admitted at a
special briefing.
</P>
<P>
India Friday agreed to extend by 24 hours the deadline for
pull-out of what New Delhi termed as intruders from Pakistan,
which was originally set on the first light of July 16 by the
directors general of military operations (DGMOs) of India and
Pakistan last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Press Trust of India (PTI), DGMOs of the two
countries talked to each other yesterday on the hotline to discuss
the issue of withdrawal. Details of the conversation were not
known.
</P>
<P>
While Indian troops had reached the LOC in Batalik, Kaksar and
Drass areas of Kashmir, the spokesman said, they were moving
forward for occupying heights along the LOC in Mushkoh sector.
</P>
<P>
Following the expiry of the deadline, the spokesman added, any
intruder found within Indian territory "would be shot and killed".
</P>
<P>
Since the breakout of the current conflict in Kashmir,
according of official figures published by India, Pakistan forces
suffered 698 fatalities while 410 Indian soldiers, including 25
officers, were killed with 593 others wounded and four missing.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason for us not to give the correct (casualty)
figures," the spokesman said, adding that "we have obligations to
keep the family members of every armed forces personnel informed
about their fate". 
</P>
</TEXT>
