<HEADLINE> Malaria Kills 95 in West Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaria has claimed more than 95
lives in a district of west Kenya in the past one and a half
months, health ministry officials have disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-one people died in June and 34 others in July in Uasin
Gishu District of Rift Valley Province in west Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 6,225 hospital inmates, 4,106 were infected with
malaria in June while this month there were 1,670 patients.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Assistant Minister for Health Basil Criticos said
Friday that chloroquin had become ineffective in the treatment of
the disease.
</P>
<P>
He said that malaria was found to be 80 percent resistance to
chloroquine in Uasin Gishu District of Rift Valley Province.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret that there was an acute shortage of quinine
used in the treatment of malaria. But he said patients were
responding well to Fansidar even though it was expensive.
</P>
<P>
Criticos said many patients preferred using chloroquin because
it was cheap and readily available.
</P>
<P>
Jack Nyamonga from the ministry's headquarters said malaria
cases would fall by mid-August due to a weather change. 
</P>
</TEXT>
