<HEADLINE> NATO to Remain in Albania as Partner: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli
Majko said on Saturday that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) will remain a present partner and cooperator in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Majko made this remark after he visited the command of NATO
forces on "humanitarian mission" in Albania (AFOR).
</P>
<P>
NATO is a guarantee not only for peace in the region, but also
for partnership, Majko was quoted as saying by the Albanian
Telegraphic Agency (ATA).
</P>
<P>
Concerning the settlement of NATO forces in Albania under a new
name after AFOR's mission ends, Majko noted that the name is not
important, the Albanian government will guarantee the
implementation of the plans it signed with NATO.
</P>
<P>
Majko, accompanied by John Reith, commander of AFOR, also paid
a visit to Kukes in northern Albania on Saturday. He praised the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and NATO for
their role in aid mission.
</P>
<P>
Reith said that the cooperation between NATO and Albania will
continue to be strong even in the future.
</P>
<P>
A decision on the future of NATO forces in Albania could be
expected on Monday, he added.
</P>
<P>
Albania signed a plan of partnership for peace with NATO in
February 1994, which allows some political and military
cooperation between the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
