<HEADLINE> Search for Young Kennedy Narrows to Waters Near Martha's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Searchers swept the waters
off Martha's Vineyard in Massachusetts State of the United States
Saturday, pressing a desperate hunt for John F. Kennedy Jr., son
of the former U.S. president, his wife and her sister, whose plane
had vanished on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a suitcase bearing the name of Lauren Bessette,
sister-in-law of John F. Kennedy Jr., was found on the shore of
Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
Fears grew that America's most renowned political family had
suffered another ghastly tragedy. The couple had been en route to
Cape Cod and a Kennedy cousin's wedding -- now postponed and
replaced with prayers for the missing. The plane left an airfield
in New Jersey State at 8:45 p.m. (local time) Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We're still pursuing an active search-and-rescue mission.
There's always hope," said Gary Jones of the Coast Guard office in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton spoke with members of the Kennedy
family Saturday after he was told John F. Kennedy Jr.'s plane had
disappeared, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
Kennedy, 38, is the only surviving son of the 35th president,
and was born just two months before his father's inauguration.
</P>
<P>
His father's assassination immediately thrust him into the
public eye with the poignant photo of the little boy saluting as
his funeral procession passed.
</P>
<P>
Unlike other family members, Kennedy never entered politics.
After graduating from Brown University, he went to law school and
joined the Manhattan district attorney's office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
