<HEADLINE> Seminar To Discuss India's National Youth Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- With About 94 percent of Indian
youth in the 13-21 age group are school dropouts, a seminar has
been planned to discuss a comprehensive national policy towards
youth.
</P>
<P>
India has large number of youth population among other
developing countries, totaling about 200 million (aged between 15
to 24), according to B. Rao, Chairman of New Delhi-based Urivi
Vikram Charitable Trust.
</P>
<P>
With youth population expected to go up to 510 million by 2016,
which is about 40 percent of the entire population in the country,
India needs a matching infrastructure, a comprehensive and
progressive agenda to fulfill their growing needs and soaring
aspirations.
</P>
<P>
Aimed at thrashing out various issues confronting this
important segment of the population, a three-day seminar, "Towards
a Policy For Young Adults", will be held here from July 22 to 24.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, organized by the Urivi Vikram Charitable Trust and
the Department of Youth Affairs And Sports under the Ministry of
Human Resource Development, would be attended by representatives
of youth from all over the country, Rao told the press here today.
</P>
<P>
Experts and government officials would try to identify the
problems and needs of the young and work on a comprehensive
policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
