</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia's second largest Islamic organization
Muhammadiyah will accept whoever becomes president so long as he
or she is elected by the country's highest decision-making body,
the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR).
</P>
<P>
"The presidential election has its own mechanism. Muhammadiyah
entrusts the issue to the MPR," Muhammadiyah Deputy Chairman Abdul
Munir Mulkhan said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at Muhammadiyah University's graduation ceremony
here, Mulkhan said the escalating debate on who will be president
was caused by different perceptions among the people.
</P>
<P>
A lot of people think that the leader of a winning political
party will be automatically elected as president, he said, adding
that the June election is only to elect the 462 members of the
House of Representatives (DPR).
</P>
<P>
The remaining 38 DPR seats are reserved for the military, whose
members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
The 500 legislators along with another 200 appointed MPR
members will cast their votes in a presidential election set to
take place in November this year. (Indonesia-Presidential
Election) 
</P>
