<HEADLINE> Mysterious Disease Kills Six in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, July 18 (Xinhua) -- An unknown disease in southern
Russia has killed six people, the Itar-Tass news agency reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Although the disease has not been identified, the country's
chief sanitary doctor, Gennady Onishenko, said it could be "the
Congo-Crimean hemorrhage fever."
</P>
<P>
The infection, which started to strike victims in the Rostov
region last week, is characterized by extensive internal
hemorrhage, temperature rise and signs of herpes.
</P>
<P>
Onishenko said 81 people had contracted the disease and 50 of
them were getting ready to be checked out of hospital.
</P>
<P>
Authorities are trying to localize the infection, but will not
introduce a quarantine, Onishenko said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
