<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The supreme leader of the ruling
Afghan Taliban, Mulla Muhammad Omar Sunday said they will not
surrender to the U.S. pressure to hand over the Saudi dissident
Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Omar said Washington does not have the right to
ask for the extradition of Osama, who was accused by the States of
masterminding the bomb blasts in U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania last August.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban would welcome to embrace martyrdom but will never
succumb to the demands for expulsion of Osama, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement followed the U.S. Statement Department warning to
the Americans in Pakistan that they should be much careful as the
Afghan extremists are planning to attack U.S. interests in
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The United States recently imposed trade and economic sanctions
on the Taliban in a bid to force the group to extradite Osama.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, however, said Afghanistan and the United States
have no extradition treaty and hence they are not bound to hand
him over to Washington. 
</P>
