<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Holds Talks With New Zealand PM (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji and
visiting New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley exchanged views
today on bilateral relations, APEC and other international and
regional issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
During the talks between the two prime ministers, Zhu said that
New Zealand will host the informal leadership meeting of APEC
members this September, and Chinese President Jiang Zemin will pay
a state visit to New Zealand, adding that the visit will be a
major event in Sino-New Zealand ties and have a far-reaching
impact upon the stable development of bilateral relations since it
will be the first state visit to that country by a Chinese
President.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted that China and New Zealand have maintained a good
development momentum in bilateral ties, and the two have conducted
active dialogue and cooperation on international and regional
issues. The two countries have also registered achievements in
bilateral cooperation in the military, cultural, educational and
tourism fields.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-New Zealand trade volume witnessed a big increase last
year, compared with that in 1997, Zhu said, adding that the two
countries are both influential ones in the Asia-Pacific region and
they shoulder the common responsibility to maintain world peace
and stability, and to promote regional economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
China and New Zealand are complementary in their economies, and
China is ready to work together with New Zealand to advance
bilateral cooperation in every area, Zhu told Shipley.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said that her current China tour is aimed at boosting
bilateral friendship and exploring new ways for bilateral
cooperation in various areas. The government and people of New
Zealand are looking forward to President Jiang's state visit to
their country in September, which will be of great significance
and will promote the all-round development of bilateral friendly
cooperation, she said.
</P>
<P>
She told Zhu that New Zealand also hopes to conduct an in-
depth exchange of opinions with China to coordinate bilateral
positions to ensure more achievements at the upcoming APEC
leadership meeting in New Zealand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990718.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Holds Talks With New Zealand PM (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The New Zealand prime minister also briefed Zhu on her country'
s view on the major topics to be discussed at the upcoming APEC
meeting, and stressed that New Zealand pays great attention to
trade and investment liberalization, the strengthening of market
functions and the economic participation of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the Taiwan issue, Shipley said that her government
firmly upholds the "one China" policy, and will properly handle
the Taiwan affair strictly in accordance with the relevant APEC
memorandum of understanding. The stand was appreciated by the
Chinese premier.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier said that China highly values the role of
APEC as the most important forum for economic cooperation in the
Asia-Pacific, saying that it has made a great contribution to
enhancing regional economic cooperation, coordinating the economic
interests of its members and promoting economic growth in the
region and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Zhu said, APEC has provided an important regular
meeting place for the leaders of the major countries of the region,
and its role in resolving international, regional and bilateral
issues has been widely acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier stressed that APEC should, in accordance
with the actual situations and needs of its members, promote trade
and investment liberalization at an appropriate pace, step up
economic and technological cooperation, and help resolve problems
for members that have been hit by the Asian financial crisis, to
realize its goal of narrowing gaps between members and achieving
common prosperity.
</P>
<P>
It is the belief of the Chinese Government, he said, that APEC
will play a greater role in regional and global economic
cooperation with the economic recovery in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Since joining APEC in 1991, China has made vigorous efforts in
various fields of endeavor of the organization, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin has attended every informal
leadership meeting of the APEC since then, and has played a
constructive role in the development of the organization, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
"China will, as always, highly value the role of APEC, actively
participate in its activities, and make further contributions to
cooperation between APEC members," the Chinese premier promised.
</P>
<P>
Zhu wished the informal leadership meeting of the APEC members
this year a success.
</P>
<P>
Chinese foreign minister Tang Jiaxuan was among those present
at the talks.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand prime minister arrived here this afternoon for
a three-day working visit to China at the invitation of her
Chinese counterpart.  
</P>
