<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Team Enters UNSCOM Laboratory in Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 18 (Xinhua) -- A visiting U.N. technical team,
which is entrusted to remove toxic chemical agents left behind by
the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on disarming Iraq, entered
UNSCOM's laboratory in Baghdad on Sunday, a U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
Prakash Shah, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's representative
in Iraq, made the remarks at a press conference held in the
U.N. Baghdad Monitoring and Verification Center (BMVC).
</P>
<P>
Shah said that in the last three days, the U.N. technical team
which arrived here on Wednesday, has been making preparations for
entering UNSCOM's chemical laboratory and biological room.
</P>
<P>
He said that at 11:30 local time (8:30 GMT), accompanied by himself
and three diplomatic observers from the Chinese, Russian and
French embassies in Baghdad, the U.N. team opened the laboratory
and commenced their work.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. team groups four chemical experts from the
Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) in
the Hague and an independent biological weapons expert.
</P>
<P>
They are from China, Russia, South Africa, Poland and
Germany. Yako Yalato, a Finnish, former assistant director of
BMVC, acts as guide for the U.N. team.
</P>
<P>
Shah said the U.N. team would destroy all of the mustard gas
samples and other chemical agents, close the chemical laboratory
and the biological room and then report to the U.N., adding that
the whole process will be videotaped.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. team is expected to begin the destruction of the
chemical agents and mustard gas samples from Monday morning, and
the process will take about three days, said Shah.
</P>
<P>
He said all the chemical agents would be neutralized
through chemical process inside the chemical laboratory and
biological room in a best possible manner.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and the U.N. reached an agreement last month on the
composition of the technical team to close UNSCOM's Baghdad
laboratory where one kilogram of mustard gas and VX gas were
reportedly left behind by UNSCOM before it withdrew from Iraq
last December.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM has not resumed its work of weapons inspections in
Iraq since last December when the United States and Britain
launched four-night airstrikes against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
