<HEADLINE> Hunan Faces Threat Of Major Summer Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province is
facing the threat of a major summer flooding similar to that of
1998, as a result of sustained rainfall across the province and on
the upper and middle reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Located on the middle reaches of the Yangtze, Hunan is home to
four major tributaries of that river and Dongting Lake, and
therefore has always been haunted by the problem of flooding.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from the local hydrological departments,
the water level at Chenglingji, where the Yangtze River and
Dongting Lake converge, reached the alarming height of 34 m on
July 3 and has since kept on rising.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the water level at Chenglingji to hit 35.30 m by
July 20, only slightly lower than the all-time high recorded in
the 1998 summer flooding," said an official with the Hunan
Provincial Flood Control Department.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, in the past few weeks more than 1,
000 sections of the over 3,000 km of dykes around Dongting Lake
have faced the threat of breaches under the high pressure of the
flood water.
</P>
<P>
The official added that the Hunan Provincial Government has
urged all relevant departments across the province to adopt an
around-the-clock monitoring system and make timely and full
preparations for any possible flooding.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, more than one million officials, residents
and soldiers from the People's Liberation Army (PLA) and the armed
police units stationed in cities and regions around Dongting Lake,
including Changde, Yueyang and Yiyang, have been mobilized to
patrol the lake dykes day and night.
</P>
<P>
From July to September last year, the entire Yangtze River
basin was hit by China's worst flooding in decades, resulting in
more than 3,000 deaths and direct economic losses of over 200
billion yuan. Hunan was one of the most severely afflicted
provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
