<HEADLINE> Nigeria's House Speaker Advised to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the ruling People's
Democratic Party (PDP) may have advised embattled Speaker of the
House of Representative Alhaji Ibrahim Buhari to step aside
quietly to save the reputation of the party.
</P>
<P>
Following a consultation at the weekend, party Chairman Chief
Solomon Lar, National Secretary Okwesilieze Nwodo and other top
party leaders considered the resignation option as the most
honorable in the event of the impeachment alternative.
</P>
<P>
One of the leaders said that "we are advising him to resign to
save the reputation of the party and the PDP government," The
Guardian newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The News magazine last Sunday published allegations that Buhari
is 29 and not the 36 years of age he claims to be, and that he
never attended the University of Toronto in Canada which he also
claims to be an alumnus.
</P>
<P>
After the revelation of the forgery, Chairman of the
Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) Justice Ephraim
Akpata disclosed last week that there were official discoveries of
the alleged false declaration by the security agencies.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held on Saturday in Kaduna, northern
Nigeria, Senator Idris Kuta blamed the INEC, the clerk of the
House of Representatives and PDP leaders for suppressing the
petitions against the Speaker on alleged forgery before the
magazine published the issue.
</P>
<P>
The senator said that "before this boy was elected speaker, it
was made absolutely clear that the paper that he used to contest
elections were forged."
</P>
<P>
A top presidency official was quoted as saying on Saturday, "if
he does not want to go quietly, he will only have himself to
blame. The court option will not help him."
</P>
<P>
Members of the House of Representatives have promised to take
the current issue involving Speaker Buhari to its logical
conclusion at the next sitting on Tuesday this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
