<HEADLINE> China-Made Mobile Phone Switchboards Available </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 18 (Xinhua) -- China-produced mobile phone
switchboards will be used for the first time in China Unicom's GSM
network expansion project in Guangdong Province, south China.
</P>
<P>
The mobile phone exchange system will be supplied by the
Guangzhou-based Jinpeng Mobile Telecommunication Systems Co. Ltd.
according to a contract between it and China Unicom.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, signed last Tuesday, Jinpeng will provide
China Unicom with the JPM-I mobile phone exchange system for
installation of a GSM network that will cover Guangdong's northern
and eastern mountainous areas.
</P>
<P>
The 5.85-million-yuan contract involves the supply of exchange
system that will be able to handle 20,000 calls simultaneously,
according to corporate sources.
</P>
<P>
This will help put an end to the awkward situation in China's
mobile telecommunications sector that has long been monopolized by
foreign technologies.
</P>
<P>
Jinpeng is a joint venture launched last June by the Guangzhou-
based Jinpeng Company Group, a leading Chinese telecommunications
conglomerate, and Motorola Company of the United States.
</P>
<P>
China Unicom is the country's second largest telecommunications
company after China Telecom, and its GSM network in Guangdong, a
showcase of China's market economy reforms, is now capable of
handling 880,000 simultaneous phone calls.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China Unicom's GSM network has more than 1.5 million
mobile phone subscribers, including 350,000 in Guangdong.
</P>
</TEXT>
