<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Brief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Informed sources said the experiment operation of a
1600-kilometer oil pipeline kicked off in Sudan linking the
Mukhlad basin district with the export stations near the Port
Sudan harbor, the Egyptian daily Al Alam Al Youm reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The number of fertilizer and insecticide
factories in the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) member states
increased to 48 in 1997 with an investment cost of 3.8 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Al Alam Al Youm reported Sunday that the industry which
absorbed 6400 employees experienced major development over the
past years.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- About 1 million units of personal computers (PC) are
expected to be sold in the Middle East and North Africa by the end
of this year, making the region the fastest growing computer
market only after Asia.
</P>
<P>
A latest survey conducted by the International Delta Research
Corporation also showed that Egypt came first in terms of
purchasing PCs in the region followed by Saudi Arabia and the
United Arab Emirates, the Al Alam Al Youm said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Italian oil company Eni has decided to invest 1.3
billion dollars in Egypt's oil sector in the coming four years,
the head of Eni said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The head of Eni made the announcement after a meeting with
Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal El-Ganzouri, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Eni has invested 8 billion dollars in the field of gas and oil
in Egypt over the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Dubai, the re-export center of the Middle East,
imported around 23.4 tons of gold in June, a drop of 8 percent
compared to 25.5 tons in May, said a statistical report issued by
the emirate's Department of Ports and Customs.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoted by Khaleej Times on Sunday, also shows that
a total of 31.32 tons of silver were re-exported from Dubai in
June. India has been the top destination for re-exportation of
gold and silver form Dubai over the past decades, the report
added. 
</P>
