<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh Not to Export Natural Gas Now or in Near Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh does not export its
natural gas now and will not export it in the near future, and
this is the word from both Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina and
opposition leader Khaleda Zia.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders disagree on everything except the need for
Bangladesh to keep its natural gas for domestic consumption,
unless reserves prove so huge that exports become possible.
</P>
<P>
Surveys show that the proven natural gas reserve in this South
Asian country stands at 16 trillion cubic feet (TCF), but some
World Bank experts say that Bangladesh's reserves could be as high
as 40 TCF, similar to that of the North Sea.
</P>
<P>
Some oil and gas industry experts also believe that the country
sits on one of the largest natural gas fields in the world.
</P>
<P>
However, both Hasina and Khaleda said the natural gas reserves
have not been measured accurately, arguing that the gas should be
firstly used to supply power to the 85 percent of the country's
over 128 million people who are still inaccessible to electricity.
It means that they have taken a Bangladesh-first stand on the gas
issue.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is now heavily dependent on its natural gas as a
source of primary energy with over 80 percent of electricity being
generated with gas-based power plant, and there is little or no
change for the country having an alternative energy source to
replace its natural gas source in near future, according to some
experts.
</P>
<P>
Though the Bangladeshi government is now under severe pressure
from the both multi-national and bilateral donors to take a
decision in favor of exporting natural gas, it has still remained
firm to its avowed principle of not exporting gas.
</P>
<P>
At present, the donor agencies and countries are trying hard to
convince both the government and the opposition to change their
minds and decide to export gas.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the donors have intensified their lobby among
policy-makers, political stalwarts and others concerned, press
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and other donor agencies and countries are
suggesting that Bangladesh could earn 25 billion taka (515.5
million U.S. dollars) a year by exporting gas through pipeline to
its neighboring country of India.
</P>
<P>
But, the Bangladeshi side, while commenting on the
prescription, said the issue of exporting gas would come only
after making a proper assessment of the gas reserves, the
requirement of the country and other prospects.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is now producing 925 million cubic feet (MCF) of gas
every day to meet the domestic need, and the demand for gas within
the country would reach 1,235 MCF per day next year against the
supply of about 1,000 MCF showing a deficit of 235 MCF of gas.
</P>
<P>
If the country continues to produce 1,000 MCF of gas per day,
the present explored reserves will continue upto the year 2015,
and during this period of time, the total deficit would reach
2,600 MCF, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The question whether Bangladesh should export its natural gas
has been in focus in the news media, among the experts and
economists and of course among the government officials for some
time now.
</P>
<P>
Opinions on the above question belong to two distinct groups --
one, namely, the foreign oil companies and a lobby supporting
their view argues that Bangladesh should export its natural gas to
help its economy get long demanding foreign earnings, and the
other group, which includes some national experts and leaders,
have expressed their concern over the fact that the country may be
plunged into serious trouble if the present modest gas reserve is
exhausted by allowing pipeline export without ensuring alternative
energy resource for the near future or for the next generation.
</P>
<P>
The national policy-makers should not frame a gas policy on the
basis of foreign companies' "theoretical suggestion" for a very
large gas reserves, and the government must take the
presently-proved gas-reserve estimate into consideration while
considering the question of gas export, stressed Dr. Bedrul Imam,
professor in geology of the Dhaka University.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh should certainly wait for a very large gas deposit
to be proved to satisfy the country's energy need for the next 40
years before it considers gas export, Imam emphasized, adding that
the government should certainly not contemplate exporting gas to a
foreign country with the presently modest gas reserve in hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
