<HEADLINE> 300,000  Displaced People in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Uganda had 0.3 million displaced
people inside and 10,000 people in exile in 1998, an international
organization report said.
</P>
<P>
Up to 70,000 Ugandans were internally displaced in 1996 and the
figure rose to 0.3 million in 1998, said the World Disaster Report
1999 compiled by the International Federation of Red Cross and Red
 Crescent Societies.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, there were 20,000 Ugandans living outside the country
as refugees and asylum seekers and the figure declined to 15,000
in 1994 and further to 10,000 in 1998, according to the report
available here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The report also reveals that by last year, up to 180,000 people
were living in Uganda as refugees and 300,000 in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"Regional conflict in the Great Lakes region and civil strife in
southern Sudan contributed to the tensions in Uganda, not least by
causing population movement," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The publication also said Uganda remains among the world's
poorest countries, plagued by internal conflicts and natural
disasters, despite significant economic progress in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
