<HEADLINE> Iran Blames Opposition Groups for Recent Unrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Sunday blamed the
opposition groups for being behind the recent chaos triggered by a
police crackdown on student protests against the new press law
and the closure of leading moderate daily Salam (Hello).
</P>
<P>
The Intelligence Ministry said in a statement that
"orchestrated attempts had been launched by certain
counter-revolutionary groups to misuse the recent events," the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Based on the information obtained and confessions made by
those arrested, some of the people or groups who played an active
role in the recent tumults, had been supported and guided from
abroad and constantly received money through specific bank
accounts," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry failed to give the names of the
opposition groups it pointed its fingers at.
</P>
<P>
Some Iranian dailies claimed that the Mujahedin Khalq
Organization (MKO), which was outlawed by Tehran and now based in
Iraq, was behind the unrest.
</P>
<P>
Iranian university students took to the streets and clashed
with the police after the latter launched an unauthorized assault
on the Tehran University dormitory, beating up and arresting
students who gathered at a rally protesting the new press law and
the closure of the Salam daily on July 8.
</P>
<P>
The student protests lasted for six days and were suppressed by
a massive rally arranged by the conservatives on Wednesday in
support of the conservative supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
Western countries believed that the student protests are an
indication of Iran's spiraling power struggle between the
conservatives, who dominated most of the country's state organs,
and the moderates, supporters of the reformist President Mohammad
Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei on Tuesday also blast "foreign and domestic enemies"
for involving in the unrest and warned students of "the black
hands of the enemies." 
</P>
