<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Muhammadiyah to Accept MPR's Decision on Presidential Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's second largest Islamic
organization Muhammadiyah will accept whoever becomes president so
long as he or she is elected by the country's highest
decision-making body, the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR).
</P>
<P>
"The presidential election has its own mechanism. Muhammadiyah
entrusts the issue to the MPR," Muhammadiyah Deputy Chairman Abdul
Munir Mulkhan said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at Muhammadiyah University's graduation ceremony
here, Mulkhan said the escalating debate on who will be president
was caused by different perceptions among the people.
</P>
<P>
A lot of people think that the leader of a winning political
party will be automatically elected as president, he said, adding
that the June election is only to elect the 462 members of the
House of Representatives (DPR).
</P>
<P>
The remaining 38 DPR seats are reserved for the military, whose
members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
The 500 legislators along with another 200 appointed MPR
members will cast their votes in a presidential election set to
take place in November this year.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent President B.J. Habibie has been nominated by the
Golkar Party for the upcoming presidential election. He is in
competition with Megawati Soekarnoputri, female leader of the
Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle which has won the June 7
general election.
</P>
<P>
Recently, some Muslim groups have aired their disagreement over
the possibility of a female president in the world's largest
Muslim country.
</P>
<P>
The United Development Party has recommended that only a male
Muslim candidate be eligible for the presidency. Some public
figures have also stated that a woman should not be permitted to
lead the country.
</P>
<P>
But some prominent figures stated that Megawati has more right
than any other contenders to become the country's next president
because her party gained the lion's share of votes in the
election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
