<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growth In China's Township Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- In the first half of the year,
China's township enterprises reported added value output of 1195.7
billion yuan, up 16.5 percent on a year-on-year basis, with
industrial added value output up 14.2 percent to 828.3 billion
yuan, according to Agriculture Ministry statistics.
</P>
<P>
They also indicate a recovery in exports, which amounted to 346.
6 billion yuan, up 7.2 percent from the same period last year.
Profits reached 263.7 billion yuan, a jump of 14.9 percent on a
year-on-year basis and taxes exceeded 90 billion yuan, up 14.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months, the private sector in these
enterprises continued to grow, with added value output accounting
for 56.8 percent of total output, up 2.3 percent. Jiang Yongtao,
the Ministry's chief economist and director of its Township
Enterprise Bureau, attributes this good performance mainly to
measures to stimulate domestic demand and the enterprises' effort
to adjust production to the market.
</P>
<P>
They still face difficult problems in their development,
however, he says, because banks are reluctant to lend them money,
there are unreasonable charges by some local government
departments, and there are growing restrictions by some countries
on Chinese exports. And, with China's industrial and environmental
protection policies, a large number of the small township steel
mills, coal mines, paper mills, and cement plants are being shut
down, which has affected the middle and western parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Their development in the middle and western parts of the
country slowed down in the first six months, with added value
output, profits, and exports 5 to 10 percent less than for those
enterprises in the East.
</P>
<P>
Economists say that these enterprises are still not able to
compete with state-owned enterprises on an equal footing, so it is
extremely important for the government to give them more support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
