<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Sticks to One-China Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan and Tibet are the
integrated parts of China and no one can change this fact,
Nepalese leaders told a visiting Chinese delegation here Sunday,
refuting Lee Teng-hui's recent separatist remarks on cross-Strait
relations.
</P>
<P>
Nepal's clear and consistent stand is that Taiwan and Tibet are
integrated parts of China and Nepal will stick to the one-China
policy now and forever, said former prime minister Sher Bahadur
Deuba and main opposition leader Madhav Kumar Nepal when meeting
with a delegation of the China Association for International
Friendly Contact Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
Sher Bahadur Deuba, member of the central committee of the
ruling Nepali Congress, said that the Tibet and Taiwan issues are
China's internal affairs and Nepal respects the Chinese
government's stand on this matter.
</P>
<P>
"Taiwan is one part of China, there is no compromise on this
issue," said Madhav Kumar Nepal, general secretary of the
Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist-Leninist, CPN-UML), the
main opposition party.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Nepal supports China's policy on Taiwan and
Tibet and opposes any anti-China activities based in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also attached great importance to the trade
relations between Nepal and China and called on Chinese
businessmen and investors to come to Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Sher Bahadur Deuba said Nepal is making great efforts to
attract investments from China on hydro-power projects, tourism
and hotel construction among others.
</P>
<P>
Madhav Kumar Nepal suggested that more routes between Nepal and
Tibet should be opened to promote bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation is here for a visit from July 17 to July
22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
