<HEADLINE> Wounded American Scholars Rescued In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Two American scholars who were
wounded in a traffic accident during a scientific study tour in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uigur Autonomous Region early this
morning have been rescued by the Chinese air force, the local
government said here today.
</P>
<P>
The two are Katherine Mino, 49, a female professor of oriental
fine arts history with Chicago University, and Roger Covey, 45,
president of the U.S.-based Tang Research Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The two were carrying out field study in Qiemo County in
southern Xinjiang when the accident occurred. Their Chinese
companion and guide, Professor Luo Xin from the prestigious
Beijing University, was also injured.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the accident, the Qiemo County government formed
a rescue team and also sought assistance from an air force unit
stationed in Xinjiang. The unit immediately sent out a helicopter
to the spot of the accident, which, after four hours of flight,
carried the injured back to Urumqi, capital of Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
The three scholars were hospitalized at the PLA Urumqi General
Hospital, one of the local leading medical institutions, and
according to hospital sources, both Americans were in good
conditions after emergency treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
