<HEADLINE> Tanzania Urges Close Economic Ties with Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa
on Sunday stressed the importance of forging robust economic
relations with Egypt, saying his talks with Egyptian Presidnet
Hosni Mubarak are ``quite constructive.''
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Egypt's Middle East News Agency, Mkapa
said close economic cooperation between Tanzania and Egypt can be
achieved through increasing visits by trade missions of the two
countries and holding joint industrial fairs.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who will end a four-day visit to Egypt in the day, held
two rounds of talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on
bilateral ties and issues in Africa.
</P>
<P>
A joint cooperation commission, set up in 1986, is due to meet
later this year, to be co-chaired by foreign ministers of both
countries, Mkapa said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the commission to focus on ways of enhancing
cooperation between the two countries' private sectors, proposing
that the taxation issues be streamlined.
</P>
<P>
He eulogized a trilateral pact grouping his country, Egypt and the
United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization, under which
Egypt helps Tanzania develop irrigation, agriculture and animal
husbandry by sending experts there.
</P>
<P>
He added that he has met with Egyptian businessmen and asked
them to do business in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Mkapa also discussed with Mubarak issues in
Africa. He said Tanzania and Egypt will continue coordination in
seeking ways to help bring an end to the conflicts on the
continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
