<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Road Accidents Claim 8 Kenyan Lives Everyday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- By July 13, 1,484 people had died
on the road this year in Kenya compared with 1,628 in the same
period of 1998, an average eight lives per day, police have said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that most accidents happened during weekends
and holidays. Last weekend alone 18 people died on roads and
during the July 3- 4 weekend, 29 died in separate accidents, the
Sunday Standard reported.
</P>
<P>
According to senior superintendent Mary Wafeka of the Highway
Traffic Headquarters, Kenya's roads of death are rising and the
biggest causes of the accidents are speeding and overloading.
</P>
<P>
Wafeka said the poor conditions of most roads had contributed
enormously to the escalating death toll on roads and many people
now fear to travel on the tattered roads.
</P>
<P>
She also attributed the road carnage to overloading,
unwillingness to comply with traffic rules and road signs, vehicle
defects, road unworthy conditions of some vehicles and improper
overtaking.
</P>
<P>
"The police are now taking action against overloading," she
said, adding the drivers for overloading will be taken to court
and be charged.
</P>
<P>
There had been 1,180 fatal accidents this year, causing 5,343
people seriously injured, 287 more than last year's figure, Wafeka
added.
</P>
<P>
It is learnt that the Association of Kenya Insurers has so far
lost two billion shillings (some 30 million U.S. dollars) this
year in accident claims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
