<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian City Council Workers to be Paid More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Local Government
and Housing of Zambia has accepted a 40, 000 Kwacha (about 16 U.S.
dollars) salary hike across the board for council workers agreed
between Zambia United Local Authorities Workers Union (ZULAWU) and
the Local Government Association of Zambia (LGAZ).
</P>
<P>
Sunday Times of Zambia quoted Local Government Minister Bennie
Mwiinga as saying here Saturday that his ministry has in
consultations with LGAZ accepted the wage increase but that this
is dependent on the individual council's ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will however continue consulting with other
relevant wings of government to secure a constant source of
revenue to meet the cost of the increase by all councils, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mwiinga said he will consult on the implications that may have
after implementing the collective agreement. Eight billion Kwacha
(about 3.2 million dollars) will be required to meet the cost.
</P>
<P>
Mwiinga however regretted that ZULAWU has refused to accept the
offer and opted to declare a dispute, thereby shelving all other
ideas discussed and agreed upon relating to financing of local
government.
</P>
<P>
He said it is sad that the union is insisting on the signing of
the collective agreement document regardless of whether or not
individual councils are able to implement the revised salaries and
conditions of service to make it binding on all councils.
</P>
<P>
"This is crucial because if people can't pay what they have
agreed upon, then it is pointless to sign the document," he said.
</P>
<P>
A month ago local authority workers went on strike in protest
against delayed signing of the collective agreement and adequate
funding of councils for increased salaries and conditions of
service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
