<HEADLINE> Hunt for August 7 Bombing Terrorists Intensified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government has
intensified the hunt for terrorists responsible for the bombings
of Nairobi in Kenya and Dar es Salaam in Tanzania on August 7 last
year.
</P>
<P>
A reward of five million U.S. dollars (350 million Kenyan
shillings) is being offered for information leading to the arrest
of eight suspects, including the alleged financier, Saudi
billionaire Osama bin Laden, the Sunday Nation newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The bounty is out on the heads of other alleged top terrorists
including Muhammad Atef and Mustafa Mohammed Fadhil, who are
alleged to have masterminded the August 7 bombings.
</P>
<P>
The almost simultaneous bombings in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam
left 224 people dead mainly in Nairobi, and another 5,000 people
were injured.
</P>
<P>
Four suspects who were arrested in Nairobi are facing murder
charges in a New York court, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The latest efforts to get the prime bombing suspects include
advertizing in both print and electronic media, including the
internet.
</P>
<P>
The American embassy in Nairobi declined comment on the new
effort, referring inquiries to the FBI agents working with Kenyan
security officers in Nairobi in a bid to arrest more suspects, the
paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
