<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toxic-waste Ships Heading for Cape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Two huge shipments of highly
 radioactive nuclear fuel are set to pass the Cape of Good Hope
within weeks, sparking outrage from environmentalists who warn
that spillage could spell disaster.
</P>
<P>
Green groups planning to hold protests in Cape Town tomorrow
said the possibility of sea contamination through leakage or
accident could not be ruled out because of the Cape's treacherous
seas, particularly at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace has identified the two ships as the Pacific Pintail
and the Pacific Teal, both of which are owned and operated by
Pacific Nuclear Transport, a subsidiary of British Nuclear Fuels,
Sunday Times newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The Pacific Teal passed through South African waters two years
ago, provoking a storm of protest. The vessel sparked further
outrage when it breached an undertaking not to come within 200
nautical miles of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
South African Environment Minister Mohammed Valli Moosa said he
knew nothing of the planned shipment, but said he would
investigate immediately.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for British Nuclear Fuels, John Barber, confirmed
that two vessels were being prepared to ship nuclear fuel from
Europe to Japan. He said he would not release more details until
the ships were actually under way, but added that no countries
along the route had been consulted.
</P>
<P>
In Europe, Greenpeace said the shipments contained "enough
fissile material to construct 60 nuclear bombs, more than the
entire Indian and Pakestani nuclear arsenals."
</P>
<P>
Although there were three possible routes the ships could
follow, the one around the Cape was the most likely, Greenpeace
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990718.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changsha Cinema Tries New Way to Attract Moviegoers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Moviegoers in Changsha, capital
of central China's Hunan Province, can now see a film and pay for
the ticket afterwards.
</P>
<P>
And they don't have to worry about the price, because they can
pay whatever they like when they leave the cinema.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to attract a larger audience, the Changsha Film
City, one of the largest cinemas in Changsha, has been running its
business in this way for more than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Outside the movie theater people see an appealing advertisement
that reads "You can see the film 'Unusual Love' in an unusual way:
first enjoy, then pay as much as you like."
</P>
<P>
The cinema's manager, who gave his name as Huang, said that
after a week-long experiment, the cinema found out that its box
office take was unexpectedly high, and decided to continue this
gimmick.
</P>
<P>
He said most of the audience paid for their tickets after
seeing the film in amounts anywhere from four or five yuan each to
as high as 50 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Some moviegoers admitted that they were first attracted to the
cinema by its advertisement, but then they found that the film "
Unusual Love" was really worth their time and money.
</P>
<P>
They said the film, which features a love story between a
doctor's assistant and her husband who lose consciousness for 19
years, is an excellent one, very touching and true to life.
</P>
<P>
Huang noted that good Chinese films do appear from time to time
thanks to the efforts of a new generation of directors and
producers, though many Chinese moviegoers have lost interest in
Chinese films because of their mediocrity and lack of creativity.
</P>
<P>
With new ways of attracting an audience such as this one,
people may eventually give up their prejudice against Chinese
films and help lift the sluggish domestic film industry out of its
doldrums, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
