<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arctic Samples From China's North Pole Expedition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese expedition to the
North Pole has obtained its first group of samples from the
Chukchi Sea and this has led to some interesting observations.
</P>
<P>
They have collected 13 boxes of samples from drilling at 5
spots, with sample more than 3 meters in length, according to
Doctor Gao Aiguo, a marine geologist. The samples contain
information about the environment for more than 100,000 years, he
says, because two or three centimeters represent a thousand years
of development.
</P>
<P>
He says that organic matter accounts for 5 percent of the
marine deposits beneath the Arctic. Studies of these deposits can
help scientists track ancient environmental and climate changes
and in turn provide information about preventing some natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
They have also collected more than 30 bottles of samples of
creatures living at the bottom of the sea, says Zheng Fengwu, a
marine biologist, and these say something about environmental
pollution and mineral resources and studies on them will
contribute to environmental protection, mineral resource
exploration, and studies of the geological structure and changes
of climate.
</P>
<P>
The expedition will spend 10 days in the Chukchi Sea and will
conclude their visit in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
