<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Release Loan to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has finally agreed to disburse 200 million U.S. dollars to
Zimbabwe over the next 14 months starting from two weeks' time
under a new balance of payments support agreement, The Sunday Mail
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This puts an end to almost two years of an agonizing wait by
Zimbabwe to receive the much needed balance of payments support
which was expected to prop up the country's ailing economy,
strengthen the local currency as well as unlock over 300 million
U.S. dollars support from other international donors.
</P>
<P>
IMF Resident Representative Robert Franco Friday confirmed that
all the outstanding issues had now been resolved between the IMF
and the Zimbabwean government.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwean Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa signed the
Letter of Intent for the new facility on Friday night. "All the
outstanding issues have been resolved and we are ready for
disbursement in about two weeks."
</P>
<P>
This follows a recent visit to the Bretton Woods institute's
Washington headquarters by a two-man Zimbabwean delegation,
accompanied by Franco for meetings with senior IMF management.
"We have now been given the green light and there are no
outstanding issues," Franco said.
</P>
<P>
He said the IMF will also send a team to Zimbabwe next month to
discuss a three-year Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility which
comes much cheaper at 0.5 percent interest compared to the 5
percent interest charged under the standby arrangement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
