<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Krishna
Prasad Bhattarai said here Sunday that during his tenure of
office, he will foster and strengthen as much as possible the
friendship between Nepal and China.
</P>
<P>
"We want to keep and preserve and strengthen more the
friendship," he told a visiting Chinese delegation led by Li
Changshun, vice president of the China Association for
International Friendly Contact, a national non-governmental
organization in China.
</P>
<P>
Bhattarai noted that as is known to all, there are only two
countries in the world which are very important to Nepal; they are
China in the north and India in the south.
</P>
<P>
"We have been keeping very good relations with both countries,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He held that "we have been keeping very good relations with
China for hundred years," and the relations entered a new period
with the exchange of ambassadors in 1955.
</P>
<P>
"Don't believe those ill-intended remarks that we fear the
Chinese. We like them. We get political and economic support from
China and we have people-to-people contact," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I ensure you friendship from all sides (in Nepal)," he added.
He took office as prime minister of Nepal on May 31.
</P>
<P>
The six-member Chinese delegation arrived here Saturday for a
five-day visit at the invitation of the China Study Center of
Nepal, a non-governmental organization devoting to enhance
understanding in Nepal about China's science, technology, culture,
socio-economy, trade and foreign relations. 
