<DOCNO> XIE19990718.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Gold Industry Calls for Tax Exemption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Exemption of the seven percent
value-added tax (VAT) is vital to retain competitiveness of the
Thai gold industry, a veteran trader said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Jitti Tangsithipakdi, president of the Gold Traders'
Association, said at the seminar "How can the Thai gold industry
survive?" that the seven percent VAT is the key factor hindering
increasing consumption and the competitiveness of the Thai gold
industry.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the gold demand in Thailand before the economic
crisis, the total sales volume has dropped by 80 percent, and
resulted in the shutting down of more than 3,000 gold businesses
and over 100,000 goldsmiths left unemployed, Jitti said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that more gold shops will be closed and more
goldsmiths made redundant in Thailand if the industry fails to
prepare for the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) pact which takes
effect on certain products, including gold, early next year.
</P>
<P>
The freer trade will allow cheaper gold products, particularly
from Malaysia and Indonesia, to flood into the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is alone in the region in imposing a seven percent VAT
on gold transactions. Malaysia once had a tax of around 10 percent
tax on gold, but scrapped it to stimulate its gold industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
