<HEADLINE> India Declares End of War In Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 18 (Xinhua) -- India declared on Saturday that
the war in the Kargil area of Kashmir was over as what New Delhi
termed as "intruders" had withdrew from the Indian side of the
line of control (LOC), the de facto border between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
"Intrusion from Pakistan" in Kargil had practically ended and
Indian forces had already advanced to the LOC in three out of the
four sub-sectors in the combat zone, Defense Minister George
Fernandes announced here late Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
"The war in Kargil has come to an end. The last of the
Pakistani intruders have vacated our territory," Fernandes told a
fund donation meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said that the intruders had retreated from even the few
heights they were holding in the Mushkoh Valley as the extended
deadline for withdrawal expired at the first light Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
However, the Indian Army issued shoot-and-kill orders yesterday
if any Pakistan soldier or militant was found south of the LOC.
</P>
<P>
Bikram Singh, a spokesman for the Indian Army, said Saturday at
the regular news briefing that any intruder found on the Indian
side of the LOC would be treated as hostile and be shot and
killed. 
</P>
