<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Hospitals Lack Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan hospitals are in bad
need of resources and forensic experts have stopped practicing
autopsies as economic and political crisis hit the country hard.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Boris Bossio, Legal Medicine Department director in the
state of Miranda, the Caracas newspaper El Nacional reported
Saturday that a budget of 100,000 bolivars (166 U.S. dollars) a
month for autopsies is far from enough.
</P>
<P>
Forensic experts in Miranda, a state located in Caracas
metropolis with the second biggest rate of crime in the country
and the second most populated, with 2.5 million residents, have to
use their own vehicles to pick up bodies of people who died in
undetermined violent circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Besides, corpses have to be taken directly to funeral homes,
since refrigerated chambers in hospitals do not work, and no funds
are available to repair them, the paper said. 
</P>
