<HEADLINE> Meat-eating Bacteria Cause Alarm in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A hospital in Costa Rica has
suspended 50 surgical operations and declared a state of medical
emergency after six patients were diagnosed to have been infected
by a disease caused by the lethal "meat-eating bacteria."
</P>
<P>
The authorities of the Max Peralta Hospital of Cartago said
Saturday that 50 surgical operations that had been planned were
suspended, and as a preventive measure, the access of the public
to the hospital, 20 kilometers south of San Jose, had been
forbidden.
</P>
<P>
The six patients infected by the bacteria had been isolated.
</P>
<P>
Known as "necrotizing fasceitis" and also called the "meat-
eating infection," the disease is caused by a bacterium that
destroys the infected tissue under the skin.
</P>
<P>
The Cartago hospital authorities said the six patients, three
of them seriously sick, are stable and out of danger.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican Social Security Institute Medical Manager Fernando
Ferraro said the infection came from outside the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Trying to dispel panic among the populace, he said the
infection was not an epidemic, but a sheer coincidence that
several cases had occurred at the same time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
