<DOCNO> XIE19990718.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Restructure Tax Agencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- China has decided to overhaul its
tax agency sector to improve the image of tax agent institutions,
today's China Daily Business Weekly said.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Taxation (SAT) recently made an
announcement that it is launching a general campaign to uncouple
tax agent institutions from tax bureaus and purge those that have
been "illegally established", said the English newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"All tax agencies set up by or in the name of tax bureaus must
be disconnected by the end of this year," the SAT was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the China Daily, many of China's tax bureaus have
been engaged in the business of tax agents. They set up new firms
and a number of tax officials also act as tax agents.
</P>
<P>
With such close ties with tax authorities, these agencies are
illegally managed by tax bureaus, especially when competing for
clients, insiders say.
</P>
<P>
"This has, on the contrary, blunted the competitiveness of the
agents," Zhou Shaojun, director of the Beijing Zerui Taxation
Consultation Service, told the China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The profession is also infected with problems such as
underpricing, tax dodging and even corruption, and subjected to
chaos in some areas, which "causes negative effects on the society
", according to the SAT statement.
</P>
<P>
All bureau-backed agencies must be entirely unhooked from the
taxation system from the point of view of staff, accounting system,
functions and even their names, the SAT requires.
</P>
<P>
Tax agent institutions are not permitted to "transgress the
field of administration of tax bureaus, hog a market share by
misappropriating administrative power, or operate under the name
of tax authorities", says the SAT.
</P>
<P>
Tax agent institutions that were set up without the approval of
provincial or higher authorities are defined as "illegal" and are
ordered to end their business, the China Daily added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
