<HEADLINE> Nicaraguans Urged to Move Away From Volcano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A group of Czech geologists have
recommended evacuation of people from the Casita volcano foothills
to prevent a repetition of a disaster resulted from a rain-caused
landslide.
</P>
<P>
If it rains uninterruptedly for four or more days, it will be
necessary to evacuate the villages close to the volcano, said the
Czech specialists on Saturday, who made a three-month study of the
area with their colleagues of the Nicaraguan Territorial Studies
Institute.
</P>
<P>
Study coordinator Pedro Hradecky said the Pikin Guerrero sector
of the Casita volcano, 130 kilometers northeast of Managua,
presents the same signs seen before the Rolando Rodriguez
community was buried under mud and rocks.
</P>
<P>
At least 1,500 people died last year under an avalanche of
rocks and mud during the rains caused by hurricane Mitch, that
razed the Rolando Rodriguez village, located on the slopes of the
volcano.
</P>
<P>
Official results of the investigation will be revealed in
November, after the Czech geologist group have processed the
information in their country's Geological Service, added Hradecky.
</P>
</TEXT>
