<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Achieve Balance of International Payments: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- China is to realize a balance of
international payments this year despite a shrinking trading
surplus and a falling overseas investment influx, the China Daily
Business Weekly reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Although China's exports declined 4.6 percent during the first
half of the year and imports grew 16.6 percent, China still reaped
a trade surplus of eight billion US dollars. The surplus figure
for the same period last year was at 22.6 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted experts as saying that the prospects for
China's exports for the second half of the year were looking
slightly brighter, and that the country will enjoy trade surplus
for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
Song Guoqing, chief economist of the China's Securities
Executive Council, told the weekly that trade surplus of the year
would amount 10 billion US dollars. The surplus figure for last
year was at 43.6 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report also quoted an unidentified official as saying that
while China's foreign investment influx is similar to that of
exports -- the volume is declining, the sheer size is still big
enough to underpin a favorable balance of international payments.
</P>
<P>
The direct overseas investment in the first half of the year
slid 9.2 percent to 18.6 billion US dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The official said that government's unremitting efforts to
increase exports and foreign investment have been and will
continue to be an indispensable positive factor sustaining foreign
exchange influx.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign exchange reserves stood at 147 billion US
dollars by the end of June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
