<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Beats Chile 2-1 To Take Third-place </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Mexico ended the Copa America
trip with a 2-1 victory over Chile to win its second straight
third-place in the South American championship in Asuncion,
Paraguay, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mexicans' hero is Miguel Zepeda, whose goal broke the 1-1 tie
with three minutes left and brought Mexico the victory.
</P>
<P>
"I'm extremely satisfied with what we did," Mexican coach
Miguel Lapuente said.
</P>
<P>
Mexico has reached the semifinals in three of its four
appearances in the Copa America. The team defeated Chile, Peru and
Venezuela before losing to Brazil in the semi-final.
</P>
<P>
"Mexico now wants to cease being a guest at the Copa America
and to become a fixture." Lapuente said.
</P>
<P>
The game was surprisingly hard-fought for a consolation match,
with both teams pressing the attack.
</P>
<P>
Chile had an early edge, with Fabian Estay missing high on a
free kick and Zamorano firing on a breakaway that nicked the post.
</P>
<P>
However, Mexico opened the scoring in the 25th minute.
Hernandez fired from the left side and Chile's goalkeeper Ramirez
failed to hold on. The rebound went to Palencia and he tapped it
in.
</P>
<P>
Just before the half, Hernandez nearly scored on another header,
but Ramirez got a hand on it and the ball bounced off the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
Chile leveled the score in the 80 minutes. Having stolen the
ball, Raul Palacios worked a give-and-go with Jose Luis Sierra and
eluded goalkeeper Jorge Campos to score.
</P>
<P>
Seven minutes later, Zepeda got the game winner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
