<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Mexicans to Serve Six-month Bans for Doping at Copa America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Mexican national team players
Raul Lara and Paulo Cesar Chavez were suspended for six months for
testing positive for anabolic steroids at the Copa America soccer
games, the South American confederation said in Asuncion, Paraguay,
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The ban, considered relatively light, applies only in South
America and does not prevent them from playing for their clubs in
Mexico or on their national team.
</P>
<P>
The definitive sanctions fall to FIFA and CONCACAF, the
confederation for North and Central America and the Caribbean.
Those bodies are expected at least to confirm the six-month
suspension and could order a harsher penalty.
</P>
<P>
Lara and Chavez avoided the penalty imposed for a similar
offense on Uruguay's Pablo Bengoechea, who was suspended for two
years in 1989. Until now, that was the only case of doping
registered in the Copa America.
</P>
<P>
Lara and Chavez were suspended when routine tests showed traces
of steroids in their urine after a first-round game with Brazil,
which Mexico lost 2-1.
</P>
<P>
Lara was tested again after the next game, a 3-1 victory over
Venezuela, and again the result was positive, CONMEBOL said.
</P>
</TEXT>
