<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protests Over Fuel Price Hikes End in Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Ecuadorian government agreed on
Saturday to freeze fuel prices for a year, ending the two-week-
long large-scale protests staged by some social groups and the
Indians in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
President Jamil Mahuad reached agreement with the protesters
Saturday that fuel prices will be reduced to the June level and be
frozen for a year.
</P>
<P>
The agreement means the end of the protests which started on
July 5 and also the end of the state of national emergency imposed
by the government.
</P>
<P>
Fuel prices had increased 13.1 percent on average since July 1.
</P>
<P>
Early Saturday morning Mahuad also resolved the last
differences he had with the Indians and signed the covenant with
this group.
</P>
<P>
The Indians, coming from all over Ecuador, forced the
government to establish a calendar for the liberalization of bank
accounts which were partially frozen last March, on Mahuad's
orders.
</P>
<P>
The government agreed to investigate the withdrawals of huge
sums of money before the account freeze was ordered, and to
publish auditor's reports on the status of the banking system.
</P>
</TEXT>
