<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Offers Loan to Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The International
Monetary Fund (IMF) will provide Colombia with a loan of 3 billion
U.S. dollars to back its economy, reports here quoted IMF
President Michel Camdessus as saying Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus, who made the announcement through a tele-conference
during the Meeting for Productivity and Competitiveness in
Colombia's Caribbean port of Cartagena, described the credit as
the launching pad for the country's government economic program.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said the loan, the most important support measure
offered recently by the IMF to the Andean country, will contribute
to the revitalization process of Colombia's economy, and
constitute "an indispensable complement for its peace process."
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the Interamerican Development Bank (IDB)
also announced similar backing to promote confidence for the peace
talks, to be resumed next Monday with the Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia (FARC).
</P>
<P>
Colombia, facing its worst economic slump for decades, has
already adopted several austerity measures, including
recapitalizing state banks and cutting public spending to reduce
the 1999 fiscal deficit to 2.5 percent of the gross domestic
product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
