<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teenage Smokers Increasing Dramatically in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Teenage smoking has risen
dramatically in New Zealand this decade, according to two
recently-released studies.
</P>
<P>
Otago University researcher Tony Reeder found in his study that
15 percent of 5,000 Wellington fourth formers questioned in 1997
about their smoking habits lit up daily compared with eight
percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The study showed that the proportion of fourth-formers who had
smoked in the month before being questioned had jumped from 18
percent to 28 percent. Simultaneously, disapproval rates about
smoking dropped among survey participants.
</P>
<P>
The second survey, by an anti-smoking group, revealed that 38
percent of fourth-formers smoked in 1998 compared with 31 percent
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Results from the studies have led New Zealand health groups to
push for an anti-smoking campaign aimed at teenagers and have also
raised doubts about the effectiveness of the Smokefree
Environments Act.
</P>
<P>
An amendment to the Act, due to be debated in the Parliament in
10 days, would designate schools smoke free, require cigarettes to
be kept out of sight in shops, and impose harsher punishment on
the retailers who sell cigarettes to children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990718.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Govt Backed in Challenge against US Lamb Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Meat New Zealand Chairman John
Acland
said New Zealand farmers, meat processors and exporters have
"every right
to be angry at" U.S. President Bill Clinton's decision to impose
tariffs
on all lamb imports.
</P>
<P>
In the latest issue of "Meat Matters" by Meat NZ, Chairman
Acland said
his board is backing the New Zealand Government "all the way in
any
challenge it makes to the World Trade Organization (WTO)" on what
he
described as this "unacceptable U.S. decision."
</P>
<P>
The decision recently announced by President Clinton is to levy
a
tariff of nine percent on lamb imports from July 22, up to the
volume
imported in 1998 with the rate falling to six percent in the
second year
and reducing to three percent in the third year of the three-year

arrangement. Outside the quota, according to the decision, a
tariff of 40
percent will be imposed in the first year, reducing to 32 percent
and 24
percent in years two and three.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand and Australia are the major lamb suppliers to the
U.S.
market.
</P>
<P>
Over the three years, the U.S. decision "will levy a gratuitous
tax of
some 24 million NZ dollars" (about 13 million U.S. dollars) on New

Zealand sheep farmers and exporters, Acland said.
</P>
<P>
"I am shattered by this decision. It flies in the face of
statements
by the President and other members of his Administration that the
United
States is dedicated to 'free and fair' trade. It can only
undermine the
credibility of President Clinton's call to other trading nations
to join
in a new round of multilateral negotiations late this year," he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
