<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ngeny Roars Second Best Result, But Misses Oldest Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Noah Ngeny ran the second-
fastest 1,000 meters in the history, missing Sebastian Coe's world
record narrowly in the Nice Athletics Grand Prix meeting in Nice,
France, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ngeny roared round the track in two minutes 12.66 seconds, just
shy of Coe's time of 2:12.18 set 18 years ago in Oslo and the
oldest individual record in the athletics record books.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Kenyan, who has run the three fastest 1,500
meters times this season and bettered Morocco's Hicham El Guerrouj
to the mile world record two weeks ago in Rome, was paced by
fellow David Kiptoo through much of the race.
</P>
<P>
Algeria's Noureddine Morceli, Olympic 1,500 meters champion and
2,000 meters world record holder, was also expected to challenge
the mark but the former world record holder in the 1,500, mile and
3,000 failed to appear on the start line.
</P>
<P>
Olympic 800 and 1,500 gold medallist Svetlana Masterkova of
Russia attempted to break her own record in the women's 1,000
meters but fell more than two seconds short, clocking 2:32.18
despite being pushed by Mozambique's Maria Mutola.
</P>
<P>
The meeting got off to a blistering start, with Ionela Tirlea
of Romania recording the second-best time this season in the 400
meters hurdles, clocking 53.44 to edge out world champion Nezha
Bidouane of Morocco 53.48.
</P>
<P>
Ghana's Leonard Myles-Mills won the men's 100 meters in 10.12
seconds, Britain's Mark Richardson the men's 400 in 44.98 and
Sevatheda Fynes of Bahamas took the women's 200 title in 22.32.
Kenyan Paul Kosgei took the 3,000 meters steeplechase in a slow 8:
09.46. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
