<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras, O'Brien Team up to Avoid U.S. Davi s Cup Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Pete Sampras and Alex O'Brien
fought off a furious charge by the Australian duo of Mark
Woodforde and Sandon Stolle to pull out a 6-4, 6-3, 3-6, 4-6, 6-3
victory today in the doubles of the Davis Cup in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. cut Australia's lead to 2-1 in the best-of-five series
heading into Sunday's reverse singles.
</P>
<P>
The win also fuels speculation on whether U.S. captain Tom
Gullikson will replace Todd Martin with Sampras in the first match
on Sunday against world No. 2 Patrick Rafter. Jim Courier and
teenager Lleyton Hewitt will square off in the fifth match.
</P>
<P>
Despite playing in his first Davis Cup doubles since,Sampras
was effective today.
</P>
<P>
Billed as the "Rivalry for the Ages," the U.S. and Australia
are meeting for the 45th time, with the U.S. holding a 25-19 edge,
including 14-8 on American soil. The U.S. has won a record 31
Davis Cup titles and Australia is second with 26.
</P>
<P>
In other quarterfinal matchups, Slovakia and Switzerland stayed
alive with doubles wins today.
</P>
<P>
Karol Kucera and Dominik Hrbaty beat Russia's team of Yevgeny
Kafelnikov and Andrei Olhovskiy, 6-2, 6-2, 6-2 today in Moscow to
avert elimination.
</P>
<P>
Russia leads the series 2-1 and needs just one win in reverse
singles Sunday to advance to the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
Lorenzo Manta and Marc Rosset of Switzerland beat Filip Dewulf
and Christophe Rochus of Belgium 2-6, 6-1, 7-6 (9-7), 7-5 today in
Brussels to avoid elimination.
</P>
<P>
Belgium leads the series 2-1 and needs just one win in reserve
singles Sunday to reach the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
Eight-time champion France took a 2-1 lead over Brazil when the
duo of Olivier Delaitre and Fabrice Santoro beat Gustavo Kuerten
and Jaime Oncins 7-6(7-5), 6-4, 6-4 today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
